Udacity Machine Learning NanoDegree Capstone Project¶

mostafa hamed¶

Wearable devices have become extremely popular in recent years for tracking user activity. These small devices use movement and motion data obtained through internal sensors that give insights into the various types of activities that are being performed by the user. This data exploration Notebook is to better understand the preprocessed version of the dataset, it's features & targets, and how best to proceed with fitting a model to it.

Smartphone-Based Recognition of Human Activities and Postural Transitions Data Set¶

Note: This data set was obtained from the UCI Machine Learning Repository found here: http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Smartphone-Based+Recognition+of+Human+Activities+and+Postural+Transitions

with open('/content/drive/My Drive/Colab Notebooks/hapt-data/activity_labels.txt','r') as f:
    activities = [line.strip() for line in f]
activity_dict ={}
    
for activity in activities:
    if int(activity[0:2]) <= 9:
        activity_dict[activity[0]] = activity[2:]
        print('Activity #{} corresponds to {}'.format(activity[0] + ' ', activity[2:]))
    else:
        activity_dict[activity[0:2]] = activity[3:]
        print('Activity #{} corresponds to {}'.format(activity[0:2] + ' ', activity[3:]))

# plots of the variables 
def plot_variables_vs_activity(variables, title, sharex=True, sharey=True):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=4, ncols=3, sharey=sharey, sharex=sharex)
    fig.set_size_inches(20, 14)
    
    # give the plot a title
    plt.suptitle(title, fontsize=18)

    # initialize locations. 
    x_location = 0
    y_location = 0

    for activity_number in range(1, len(counts) + 1):
        # plot the current activity
        X_train[y_train['activity'] == activity_number][variables].plot(
            use_index=False, ax=axes[y_location, x_location])
        
        # set the activity title
        axes[y_location, x_location].set_title(activities[activity_number - 1])

        # update the x & y locations for subplots 
        if x_location < 2: 
            x_location += 1
        else:
            x_location = 0
            y_location += 1

# Training Function 
import time

# a function to keep track of training time
# always a good metric to keep track of for choosing between similar performing models
def train_classifier(clf, X_train, y_train):
    print ("Training {}...".format(clf.__class__.__name__))
    
    # time and training of the classifier 
    start = time.time()
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    end = time.time()
    
    total_training_time = end - start
    print ("Done!\nTraining time (secs): {:.3f}".format(total_training_time))
    
    return total_training_time # return to keep track

# Plotting functions 
tick_activities = [re.sub('[^A-Za-z\s]', ' ', x)[2:].title() for x in activities]

# Simplified confusion matrix array
def normalize_cm(confusion_matrix):
    return (confusion_matrix.astype('float') /
            confusion_matrix.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis])

def plot_confusion_matricies(training_cm, test_cm, title, questionable_annot_colors=None):
    
    # setup sub axes 
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, sharex=True, sharey=True)
    fig.set_size_inches(20, 7) # Plot figure Size 

    # Normalize the confusion matricies by row (i.e by the number of samples in each class)
    training_cm_normalized = normalize_cm(training_cm)
    test_cm_normalized = normalize_cm(test_cm)

    # plot 
    sns.heatmap(training_cm_normalized, annot=False, fmt='g', cmap='Blues', ax=axes[0])
    sns.heatmap(training_cm, annot=True, annot_kws={"size": 12, "color": "#111111"}, 
                fmt='g', alpha=0.0, cbar=False, ax=axes[0])
    
    sns.heatmap(test_cm_normalized, annot=False, fmt='g', cmap='Greens', ax=axes[1])
    sns.heatmap(test_cm, annot=True, annot_kws={"size": 12, "color": "#111111"}, 
                fmt='g', alpha=0.0, cbar=False, ax=axes[1])

    if questionable_annot_colors != None:
        for ax_num in range(2):
            for text in axes[ax_num].texts:
                if text.get_text() in questionable_annot_colors:
                    text.set_color('#fefefe')

    # labels and titles
    fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=20, x=0.47, y=1.02)
    axes[0].set_xticklabels(tick_activities, rotation=90, fontsize=12)
    axes[0].set_yticklabels(tick_activities[::-1], rotation=0, fontsize=12)
    axes[0].set_title('Training Confusion Matrix', fontsize=16)
    
    # axis labels 
    axes[0].set_ylabel('True Labels', fontsize=15)
    fig.text(0.47, -0.10, 'Predicted Labels', ha='center', fontsize=15)
   
    # second axis 
    axes[1].set_xticklabels(tick_activities, rotation=90, fontsize=12)
    axes[1].set_title('Testing Confusion Matrix', fontsize=16)
    
    # remove space and show 
    fig.subplots_adjust(wspace=0, hspace=0)
    plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, f1_score

# function used to output accuracy score, prediction time and resulting confusion matrix
# items are output as a tupled (accuracy, f1 score, confusion matrix, total pred time)
def predict_labels(clf, features, target, is_training=True):
    if is_training: 
        which_prediction = 'Training Set'
    else:
        which_prediction = 'Testing Set'
    print ("Predicting labels for {} using {}...".format(which_prediction, clf.__class__.__name__))
    
    # time and classifier prediction 
    start = time.time()
    y_pred = clf.predict(features)
    end = time.time()
    total_prediction_time = end - start 
    
    print ("Done!\nPrediction time for {} (secs): {:.3f}".format(which_prediction, total_prediction_time))
    return (accuracy_score(target.values, y_pred),
           f1_score(target.values, y_pred, average='weighted'),
           confusion_matrix(target.values, y_pred),
           total_prediction_time)

def annotate_points(what_to_anno, locs, color): 
    for i in range(len(what_to_anno)):
        plt.annotate('{:.3f}'.format(what_to_anno[i]), 
                xy = (i, what_to_anno[i]), xytext = locs[i],
                textcoords = 'offset points', ha = 'left', va = 'bottom', fontsize=12,
                bbox = dict(boxstyle = 'round,pad=0.5', fc = color, alpha = 0.8),
                arrowprops = dict(arrowstyle = '->', connectionstyle = 'arc3, rad=0', linewidth=1, color='grey'))
        
annotate_points(training_times, [(-10, 30), (-80, 60), (-10, 30), (-10, 30)], 'lightseagreen')
annotate_points(training_prediction_times, [(-30, 30), (-20, 40), (-60, 0), (5, 30)], 'tomato')
annotate_points(testing_prediction_times, [(30, 20), (50, 10), (0, -50), (-80, 5)], 'violet')

plt.axhline(1.0, color='slategrey', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)

plt.ylim(-0.02, 1.0)
plt.ylabel('Time (seconds)', fontsize=15)

plt.xlim(-0.3, 3.3)
plt.xticks(range(4), algorithm_list, rotation=0, fontsize=13)
plt.xlabel('Algorithm Type', fontsize=15)

# Naive Bayes Accuracies vs Number of Components
n_from_1_10 = list(range(1, 10, 1))
n_from_10_561 = list(range(10, 561, 25))

n_components = n_from_1_10 + n_from_10_561
nb_train_accuracies = []
nb_test_accuracies = []

for n_component in n_components:
    pca = PCA(n_components = n_component, whiten=True)
    pca.fit(X_train)
    
    clf = GaussianNB()
    clf.fit(pca.transform(X_train), y_train.activity.values)
    
    # calculate training accuracy 
    y_pred = clf.predict(pca.transform(X_train))
    nb_train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train.activity.values, y_pred)
    nb_train_accuracies.append(nb_train_accuracy)
    
    # calculate Testing Accuracy 
    y_pred = clf.predict(pca.transform(X_test))
    nb_test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test.activity.values, y_pred)
    nb_test_accuracies.append(nb_test_accuracy)

import os

# start with empty dataframes 
X_acc_raw = pd.DataFrame()
X_gyro_raw = pd.DataFrame()
!ls
# cycle through files to build the X_Raw_dataframe 
for raw_file in os.listdir('/content/drive/My Drive/Colab Notebooks/hapt-data/RawData/'):
    if raw_file != 'labels.txt': # ignore labels
        
        # create a dataframe from the file
        file_frame = pd.read_csv(('/content/drive/My Drive/Colab Notebooks/hapt-data/RawData/' + raw_file), sep=' ', header=None)
        
        # need to add the experiment ID and user ID to the dataframe
        x = list(filter(str.isdigit, raw_file))
        # x = ["0", "1", "2"]
        y = ''.join(x) # converting list into string
        numbers = y
        exp_ID = int(numbers[1]) if numbers[0] == '0' else int(numbers[0:2])
        user_ID = int(numbers[-1]) if numbers[2] == '0' else int(numbers[2:-1])
        
        # add experiment ID and user ID columns 
        file_frame['Experiment_ID'] = exp_ID
        file_frame['User_ID'] = user_ID
        
        # setup columns and append to appropriate dataframe 
        if raw_file.startswith('acc'):
            file_frame = file_frame.rename(
                columns = {0: 'tRawAcc-1', 1: 'tRawAcc-2', 2: 'tRawAcc-3'})
            X_acc_raw = X_acc_raw.append(file_frame)
        else:
            file_frame = file_frame.rename(
                columns = {0: 'tRawGyro-1', 1: 'tRawGyro-2', 2: 'tRawGyro-3'})
            X_gyro_raw = X_gyro_raw.append(file_frame)
